one                 = [[Central Time Zone|CST]]\n|utc_offset               = \u22126\n|timezone_DST             = [[North American Central Time Zone|CDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = \u22125\n|coordinates              = {{coord|48|13|59|N|101|17|32|W|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes      = <ref name=gnis/>\n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             = 1611\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP Code]]s\n|postal_code              = 58701\u201358703\n|area_code                = [[Area code 701|701]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 38-53380\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1030249<ref name=gnis>{{GNIS|1030249}}</ref>\n|blank2_name              = [[List of North Dakota numbered highways|Highways]]\n|blank2_info              = [[US 2]], [[US 2 Business|US 2 Bus.]], [[US 52]], [[US 52 Business|US 52 Bus.]], [[US 83]], [[US 83 Bypass|US 83 Byp.]]\n|website                  = [http://www.minotnd.org www.minotnd.org]\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n\n'''Minot''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=minot-nd.ogg|\u02c8|m|a\u026a|n|\u0252|t}} {{respell|MY|not}}) is a city in and the [[county seat]] of [[Ward County, North Dakota|Ward County]], [[North Dakota]], United States,<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=June 7, 2011 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531210815/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=2011-05-31 }}</ref> in the state's north-central region. It is most widely known for the [[Minot Air Force Base|Air Force base]] located approximately {{convert|15|mi}} north of the city. With a population of 40,888 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]],<ref name=\"2010 Census (City)\">{{cite web|title=2010 Census Redistricting Data (Public Law 94-171) Summary File|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_PL_GCTPL2.ST13&prodType=table |work=American FactFinder |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2 May 2011 }}{{dead link|bot=medic|date=April 2020}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Minot is the [[List of cities in North Dakota|fourth largest city]] in the state and a trading center for a large portion of northern [[North Dakota]], southwestern [[Manitoba]], and southeastern [[Saskatchewan]]. Founded in 1886 during the construction of James J. Hill's [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]], Minot is also known as \"Magic City\", commemorating its remarkable growth in size over a short time.\n\nMinot is the principal city of the [[Minot micropolitan area]], a [[United States micropolitan area|micropolitan area]] that covers [[McHenry County, North Dakota|McHenry]], [[Renville County, North Dakota|Renville]], and Ward counties<ref>[https://www.census.gov/population/www/estimates/metro_general/2006/List5.txt Micropolitan statistical areas and components] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629011245/http://www.census.gov/population/www/estimates/metro_general/2006/List5.txt |date=2007-06-29 }}, [[Office of Management and Budget]], 2007-05-11. Accessed 2008-07-27.</ref> and had a combined population of 69,540 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. In 2017, it was estimated that the population of the Minot Micropolitan Area was 77,309.<ref>Schramm, Jill.  \"Census Changes: Minot Area Growth Slows After Flood\".  ''Minot Daily News''. March 14, 2013.</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:1886rail-usgenweb-mapproject.jpg|thumb|Dakota Territory circa 1886, showing [[Burlington, North Dakota|Burlington]], at the time the county seat, and Minot, which was a smaller, unincorporated village.]]\n\nMinot came into existence in 1886, after the railroad laid track through the area. A tent town sprang up overnight, as if by \"magic\", thus the city came to be known as the Magic City, and in the next five months, the population increased to over 5,000 residents, further adding to the nickname's validity.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} The town site was chosen by the railroad to be placed on the land of then-homesteader [[Erik Ramstad]]. Ramstad was convinced to relinquish his claim, and became one of the city leaders. The town was named after [[Henry Davis Minot|Henry D. Minot]], a railroad investor, an [[ornithologist]] and friend of Hill. Its [[Arikara language|Arikara]] name is ''niwahar\u00edt saha\u00e1hkat'';<ref>{{Cite web | title = AISRI Dictionary Database Search-- Arikara. Prototype version\n| accessdate = 2012-07-08 | url = http://zia.aisri.indiana.edu/~dictsearch/cgi-bin/testengltoxsrchNP.pl?host=zia&pass=&hasfont=0&srchlang=English&srchstring=dakota&database=arika&srchtype=OR&sortlang=Indian&sndformat=mp3&maxhits=200&find=Run_Search }}</ref> its [[Hidatsa language|Hidatsa]] name is ''dibiarugareesh'', (\"Plum Coulee\").<ref>{{Cite web |title=Hidatsa Lessons Vocab2  |work=Hidatsa Language Program  |accessdate=2012-07-17  |url=http://www.neiu.edu/~linguist/hidatsa_lessons_vocab2.html#villages_dwellings_and_towns_i  |url-status=dead  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606135144/http://www.neiu.edu/~linguist/hidatsa_lessons_vocab2.html  |archivedate=2013-06-06  }}</ref>\n\nThe city was incorporated on July 16, 1887. The [[Minneapolis, St. Paul and Sault Ste. Marie Railroad]] (Soo Line) later built a line from [[Valley City, North Dakota|Valley City]] up to Canada. While initially their plan was to cross the [[Mouse River]] at [[Burlington, North Dakota|Burlington]], local interests and arguments convinced them otherwise; landholders along the new route donated the right-of-way. They reached Minot in 1893. \n\nOn July 22, 1920 a tornado passed over Minot and bore down in a coulee three miles southeast of town.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Almanac of North Dakota mysteries & oddities, 2009-2010|last=Jackson|first=William|date=2008|publisher=Valley Star Books|isbn=9780967734989|location=|pages=34|oclc=259419005}}</ref>  The tornado picked up the Andy Botz home and hurled it to the ground, killing Mrs. Botz, breaking Mr. Botz's shoulder, and slightly injuring the two Botz children who were in the house.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nMinot and its surrounding area were wide open throughout 1905\u20131920. The population grew rapidly due to railroad construction and availability of unclaimed land. Nearly complete court records of Ward County and Minot document the prevalence and different types of criminal activity, and offer strong support for the dubious title of \"crime capitol of North Dakota\". State attorney general [[William Langer]] helped clean up the town in 1917\u20131920, but by the time [[Prohibition]] had arrived in the 1920s the city had become a center of illegal activities associated with the [[Downtown Minot#High Third|High Third]] district, which were exacerbated due to the city being a supply hub of [[Al Capone]]'s liquor smuggling operations. The hotbed of alcohol bootlegging, prostitution, and opium dens that sprang up in the Downtown area soon led people to give Minot the nickname \"Little Chicago\". The smugglers used a network of tunnels (some of which were previously built for heating or deliveries) to transport and conceal the illicit cargo entering from Canada.<ref>Michael J. Martin and Glenn H. Smith, \"Vice and Violence in Ward County, North Dakota, 1905\u20131920\", ''North Dakota History,'' 1980, Vol. 47, Issue 2, pp. 10\u201321</ref>\n\nThe 1950s saw a large influx of [[United States Government|federal funding]] into the region, with the construction of [[Minot Air Force Base]] (1956\u201357) {{convert|13|mi|km|spell=in}} north of the city, and [[Garrison Dam]] (1947\u201353) on the [[Missouri River]], about {{convert|50|mi|km|spell=in}} south of Minot. In 1969, a severe flood on the [[Mouse River]] devastated the city. Afterward, the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Army Corps of Engineers]] straightened the path of the river through the city and built several flood control structures.\n\n[[File:2009-0521-ND-Minot-SooLinemuseum.jpg|thumb|250px|The Old Soo Depot Transportation Museum is housed in the historic Soo Line depot (built 1912) in downtown Minot.]]\n\nOn January 18, 2002, a [[Minot Train Derailment|severe train derailment]] west of the city sent a gigantic cloud of [[anhydrous ammonia]] toward Minot, and [[Burlington, North Dakota|Burlington]]. One man died and many of Minot's citizens were sickened and severely injured by the noxious gas, causing one of the worst major chemical accidents of the country.<ref name=CBC>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/minot-train-derailment-kills-one-injures-dozens-1.342396 CBC News, Minot train derailment kills one, injures dozens]</ref> In early 2006, court cases were heard in [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]], against [[Canadian Pacific Railway]], the owner of the derailed train. The anhydrous ammonia spill was the largest such spill in U.S. history. This incident was used by [[Eric Klinenberg]] in his book ''Fighting for Air: The Battle to Control America's Media'' as an example of the failure of mass-media, specifically local radio stations, to disseminate information to the public in an emergency.<ref>Klinenberg, Eric. ''Fighting for Air: The Battle to Control America's Media''. Holt: New York, 2008.</ref>\n\nThe [[2011 Mouse River flood]] caused extensive damage throughout the Mouse River Valley. On June 21, 2011, [[KXMC-TV]] reported that a flood of historic proportions was imminent in the Mouse River Valley, largely due to large dam releases upstream. Around 12,000 people were evacuated. On June 26, flooding exceeded previous records when the river crested at 1,561.72 feet above sea level, three feet above the previous record set back in 1881. It is estimated that 20 percent of Minot sustained damage from the flood. This figure includes over 4,100 homes which were in some way affected, 2,376 extensively damaged, and 805 damaged beyond repair. Burlington was also severely damaged during this time.<ref>{{cite news |title='It's a sad day' \u2014 Crest could be 10 feet higher than June 1 |first=Kim |last=Fundingsland |url=http://www.minotdailynews.com/page/content.detail/id/555952/-It-s-a-sad-day----Crest-could-be-10-feet-higher-than-June-1.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110624211855/http://minotdailynews.com/page/content.detail/id/555952/-It-s-a-sad-day----Crest-could-be-10-feet-higher-than-June-1.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 24, 2011 |newspaper=[[Minot Daily News]] |date=June 21, 2011 |accessdate=April 6, 2012 }}</ref><ref>The Minot Convention and Visitor's Bureau. {{cite web|url=http://visitminot.org/smartmail/newsletterview.asp?NLID%3D75%26UID%3D156 |accessdate=September 11, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}. Retrieved 9/11/2011</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n{{Main|Geography of Minot, North Dakota}}\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|17.45|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|17.43|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.02|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2012-06-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125061959/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=2012-01-25 }}</ref>\n\n===Neighborhoods===\n{{main|List of neighborhoods in Minot, North Dakota}}\n\nMinot is commonly divided into three major divisions. These divisions are [[North Hill, Minot|North Hill]], the Mouse River Valley and [[South Hill, Minot|South Hill]]. North Hill is the area roughly north of Eleventh Avenue North and Northwest Avenue. South Hill is a broad area south and west of Valley Street and Fifth Avenue South. West of Sixth Street West, South Hill dips sharply to the southwest. The limits of South Hill are less clearly defined than North Hill. Though the neighborhood levels out past Sixteenth Street South, the name South Hill is generally applied to all areas south up to the city limits. Neighborhoods in the Mouse River Valley include [[Bel Air, Minot|Bel Air]], [[Downtown Minot|Downtown]], [[Eastwood Park Historic District|Eastwood Park]], [[Oak Park, Minot, North Dakota|Oak Park]] and [[West Minot]].\n\n===Region===\nMinot is located on the [[Drift Prairie]] of northwestern [[North Dakota]]. Minot is at {{coord |48|13|59|N|101|17|32|W|type:city_region:US-ND}},<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> about {{convert|100|mi|km}} north of [[Bismarck, North Dakota|Bismarck]]. The [[Mouse River]], or Souris River, runs through the city west to east.\n\nImportant cities in the region for which Minot is the trading center include [[Burlington, North Dakota|Burlington]], [[Velva, North Dakota|Velva]], [[Garrison, North Dakota|Garrison]], [[Stanley, North Dakota|Stanley]], [[Bottineau, North Dakota|Bottineau]], [[Rugby, North Dakota|Rugby]], and [[New Town, North Dakota|New Town]].\n\nMinot is almost entirely land; the Mouse River, its oxbow lakes, and a few creeks take up just 0.14% of the city's total area.\n\nThe elevation of the river at the city center is {{convert|1,540|ft|m}} [[AMSL|above sea level]].<ref>[[National Weather Service]], Advanced Hydrologic Prediction Service, [http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=bis&gage=mion8&view=1,0,1,0,1,1,1,1%22]</ref>{{Failed verification|date=April 2012}}  The valley sits some {{convert|160|ft|m}} below the surrounding plains; the elevation at the [[Minot International Airport]] on \"North Hill\" is {{convert|1,716|ft|m}}. The city has several small horseshoe-shaped oxbow lakes within its limits near the river, created due to the Mouse's meandering course.\n\n===Grid and address system===\nThe city is laid out on a grid-based street system. Streets run north-south and avenues run east-west. Streets are numbered by their block distance east or west of Main Street. Similarly, Avenues are numbered north and south of Central Avenue. There are four city quadrants (NW, SW, SE, NE) to describe the exact location of any given address. Main Street addresses are simply designated North and South. Central Avenue addresses are simply designated East and West. The grid addressing system carries over into the rural areas of [[Ward County, North Dakota|Ward County]], making the county one of only three that do not follow the statewide grid system in North Dakota (the others being [[Burleigh County]] and [[Grand Forks County]]).\n\n===Mouse River===\nThe [[Mouse River]] divides the city approximately in half, north and south. The valley rises to the plains both north and south of the river. Although there are names for certain features of these hills, such as Anthony Hill on South Hill, there are no general names for these topographical features. The northern rise and the plateau north of it are referred to as '''North Hill''' and the southern rise and plateau south of it are referred to as '''South Hill'''.<ref>[https://archive.today/20130127034902/http://www.kfyrtv.com/News_Stories.asp?news=59204 Castro, Jenny.  \"City Budget Adding Jobs\". KFYR]</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nMinot experiences a [[humid continental climate]] with warm summer ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: ''Dfb'') in its marginal zone receiving sufficient precipitation for such category, being that during the year it exhibits great temperature variations as in [[Central Asia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.eng.unimelb.edu.au/mpeel/koppen.html|title=Updated K\u00f6ppen-Geiger climate map of the world|last=|first=|date=|website=people.eng.unimelb.edu.au|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref> Summers range from warm to moderately hot, with frequent [[thunderstorm]] activity. Winters are typically bitterly cold and snowy, with high winds and below-freezing temperatures for weeks at a time. Lows below {{convert|0|\u00b0F|0}} occur on about 39 days during the winter, while temperatures reach {{convert|90|\u00b0F|0}} on 14 days per summer, and in some years reach {{convert|100|\u00b0F|0}}.<ref>[[National Climatic Data Center]], Monthly Station Normals (1971\u20132000) for North Dakota, [http://cdo.ncdc.noaa.gov/climatenormals/clim81/NDnorm.txt] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814171347/http://cdo.ncdc.noaa.gov/climatenormals/clim81/NDnorm.txt |date=2014-08-14 }}. Retrieved 20 November 2006.</ref>  The average annual snowfall total is {{convert|43|in|cm}}.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{Weather box|location = Minot, North Dakota (southern suburb), 1981\u20132010 normals, extremes 1905\u2013present<ref>The station is located at {{coord|48.1803|N|101.2964|W|type:landmark_region:US-ND}}.</ref>\n|collapsed = \n|single line = Y\n|Jan high F = 18.6\n|Feb high F = 23.3\n|Mar high F = 35.1\n|Apr high F = 53.3\n|May high F = 65.6\n|Jun high F = 74.2\n|Jul high F = 80.2\n|Aug high F = 80.1\n|Sep high F = 68.6\n|Oct high F = 53.9\n|Nov high F = 35.6\n|Dec high F = 21.9\n|year high F= 50.9\n|Jan low F =  0.8\n|Feb low F =  5.4\n|Mar low F = 17.0\n|Apr low F = 30.2\n|May low F = 42.2\n|Jun low F = 52.4\n|Jul low F = 56.8\n|Aug low F = 54.4\n|Sep low F = 44.4\n|Oct low F = 31.7\n|Nov low F = 17.9\n|Dec low F =  4.9\n|year low F= 29.8\n|Jan record high F =  59\n|Feb record high F =  64\n|Mar record high F =  80\n|Apr record high F =  98\n|May record high F = 105\n|Jun record high F = 109\n|Jul record high F = 109\n|Aug record high F = 106\n|Sep record