/www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=May 26, 2013}}</ref><br>2018 Estimate<ref name=\"2018 Pop Estimate\">{{cite web|title=Population Estimates|url=https://census.gov/data/tables/2018/demo/popest/total-cities-and-towns.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=May 24, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\">{{cite web|title=U.S. Census website|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-06-14}}</ref> of 2010, there were 40,888 people, 17,863 households, and 9,978 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|2345.8|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 18,744 housing units at an average density of {{convert|1075.4|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 90.2% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 2.3% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 3.2% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.9% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Race (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.6% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 2.7% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 2.7% of the population.\n\nThere were 17,863 households of which 26.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 42.1% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 9.6% had a female householder with no husband present, 4.1% had a male householder with no wife present, and 44.1% were non-families. Of all households 34.9% were made up of individuals and 11.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.20 and the average family size was 2.86.\n\nThe median age in the city was 33.8 years. 21.1% of residents were under the age of 18; 14% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 26.7% were from 25 to 44; 23.2% were from 45 to 64; and 15% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 49.3% male and 50.7% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]] of 2000, there were 36,567 people, 15,520 households, and 9,265 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 2,513.1 per square mile (970.4/km\u00b2). There were 16,475 housing units at an average density of 1,132.3 per square mile (437.2/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 93.18% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 1.34% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 2.76% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.62% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.07% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.49% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.54% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.47% of the population.\n\nThe most populous ancestry groups in the city are [[Germany|German]] (40.8%), [[Norway|Norwegian]] (32.3%), [[Ireland|Irish]] (8.7%), [[England|English]] (5.4%), [[Sweden|Swedish]] (4.2%) and [[France|French]] (3.2%).\n\nThere were 15,520 households, of which 28.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 46.6% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 10.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 40.3% were non-families. Of all households 32.5% were made up of individuals and 12.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.27 and the average family size was 2.90.\n\nIn the city the population was spread out with 23.2% under the age of 18, 13.3% from 18 to 24, 27.4% from 25 to 44, 20.7% from 45 to 64, and 15.4% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 35 years. For every 100 females, there were 93.1 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 89.0 males.\n\nAs of 2000 the median income for a household was $32,218, and the median income for a family was $42,804. Males had a median income of $30,283 versus $20,023 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $18,011. About 8.8% of families and 12.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 16.0% of those under age 18 and 8.9% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Law and government==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=October 2010}}\nThe mayor of Minot is Shaun Sipma. As mayor he chairs the 7-member City Council, but only casts a vote to break a tie. The day-to-day affairs of the city are handled by the City Manager, currently Tom Barry.\n\nMinot uses the [[Council\u2013manager government|Council\u2013manager]] system of government. Seven councilmen are elected from 7 city wards to four-year terms. Elections are arranged such that one councilman from each ward is elected in every even-numbered year. The mayor of Minot is elected to a four-year term as well; the last mayoral election was in 2018. All city offices are nonpartisan.\n\nCity elections are held in June in [[North Dakota]], along with the state [[primary election]].\n\nWhile the city's leadership has been trending towards the conservative, Minot's liberal factions have been active in recent years and have had somewhat more success than in other areas of the state.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n===Northwest Area Water Supply===\n{{Main|Northwest Area Water Supply}}\nThe Northwest Area Water Supply (NAWS) has had disputes with the Canadian government over a plan calling for water to be pumped from [[Lake Sakakawea]], then to Minot for treatment, and then on to large stretches of Northwest North Dakota.\n\nMinot voters decided in 1998 to levy a 1% sales tax to go towards the construction of NAWS; this tax fund was found in court to have been illegally diverted towards economic development purposes.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} A lawsuit was filed against the city and it was ordered to return the misappropriated funds to the NAWS fund. By that time, the money had already been spent, and the city instead voted to issue a special assessment on city water bills to raise the funds.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n==Economy==\n\n===Largest employers===\nAccording to the City's 2013 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minotnd.org/pdf/finance/cafr13.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140713091218/http://www.minotnd.org/pdf/finance/cafr13.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 13, 2014|title=City of Minot 2013 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report|page=147|accessdate=June 16, 2014|date=June 16, 2014}}</ref> the largest employers in the city are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Employer\n! # of Employees\n|-\n|1\n|[[Minot Air Force Base]]\n|6,754\n|-\n|2\n|[[Trinity Health (Minot, North Dakota)|Trinity Health]]\n|2,066\n|-\n|3\n|[[Minot Public Schools]]\n|1,020\n|-\n|4\n|[[Cognizant]] (ING Minot Service Center)\n|600\n|-\n|5\n|[[Minot State University]]\n|444\n|-\n|7\n|Kalix (MVAW)\n|400\n|-\n|9\n|[[BNSF Railway|BNSF Railroad]]\n|350\n|-\n|10\n|City of Minot\n|343\n|-\n|11\n|[[Walmart]]\n|300\n|-\n|12\n|MLT Inc.\n|255\n|-\n|13\n|[[Menards]]\n|250\n\n|-\n|15\n|[[Ward County, North Dakota|Ward County]]\n|218\n|-\n|16\n|[[SRT Communications]]\n|215\n|-\n|17\n|[[Baker Hughes|Baker-Hughes]]\n|210\n|-\n|18\n|Westlie Motors\n|200\n|-\n|19\n|Central Trenching\n|175\n|-\n|20\n|PumpCo\n|175\n|-\n|21\n|Ryan Family Dealerships-Minot\n|157\n|-\n|22\n|Cameron Oil\n|150\n|-\n|23\n|Choice Hotels International, Inc.\n|150 (2011)\n|-\n|24\n|Dakota Boys & Girls Ranch\n|129\n|-\n|25\n|Grand International\n|120 (2012)\n|-\n|26\n|First Western Bank\n|116\n|-\n|27\n|Pure Energy/FMC Technology Completion Service\n|115\n|-\n|28\n|Weatherford\n|115\n|-\n|29\n|Enbridge\n|105\n|-\n|30\n|[[United States Postal Service]]\n|105\n|-\n|31\n|Colter Energy\n|100\n|-\n|32\n|Farstad Oil\n|\n|-\n|33\n|[[Minot Daily News]]\n|\n|-\n|34\n|International Inn\n|\n|-\n|35\n|Dakota Square Mall\n|\n|}\n\nMinot's economy depends on the [[Minot Air Force Base|Air Force Base]] located {{convert|13|mi|km}} north of town making the city's economy more robust than other cities of its size due to its large service area; however, it is beset by significant problems with enterprise capital and wage standards.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} About 30% of Minot residents work two or more jobs, and two-thirds of households earn less than the national median household income.\n\nING/ReliaStar established a service center in Minot in December 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://minotusa.com/ |title=Minot Area Development Corporation |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMinot has seen a huge increase in population and infrastructure investments in the last several years with the expanding drilling (using the '[[hydrofracking|frac]]' petroleum extraction technique) of oil in the [[Bakken Formation]] and [[Three Forks Group]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2016599974_dakotaoil25.html |work=The Seattle Times |first=Larry |last=Oakes |title=North Dakota: where the jobs are |date=October 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027122400/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2016599974_dakotaoil25.html |archivedate=October 27, 2011 }}</ref> The State of North Dakota has a website detailing daily oil activity.<ref>https://www.dmr.nd.gov/oilgas/dailyindex.asp</ref>\n\n==Education==\nThe [[Minot Public Schools]] system operates ten elementary schools (K-5) within the city: Bel Air,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid%3D3 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205035814/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=3 |archivedate=2012-02-05 }}</ref> Edison,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid%3D21 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205035839/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=21 |archivedate=2012-02-05 }}</ref> Lewis and Clark,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid%3D26 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205035850/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=26 |archivedate=2012-02-05 }}</ref> Lincoln,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid%3D23 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205035855/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=23 |archivedate=2012-02-05 }}</ref> Longfellow,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid%3D24 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205035900/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=24 |archivedate=2012-02-05 }}</ref> McKinley,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid%3D25 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205035938/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=25 |archivedate=2012-02-05 }}</ref> Roosevelt,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid%3D29 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205040005/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=29 |archivedate=2012-02-05 }}</ref> Perkett,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid%3D28 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205035952/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=28 |archivedate=2012-02-05 }}</ref> Sunnyside,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid%3D30 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205040100/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=30 |archivedate=2012-02-05 }},</ref> and Washington.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectiondetailid%3D311 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205040113/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectiondetailid=311 |archivedate=2012-02-05 }}</ref> The district also operates Bell Elementary, located about five miles southeast of Minot.\nJefferson Elementary was closed in 2003. The old Washington Elementary building was closed at the end of 2007 and the students moved to a new building which was renovated from an old health care center. There are also two elementary schools (K-6) on the [[Minot Air Force Base]]: Dakota<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=20%20%0D |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070424143604/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=20 |archivedate=2007-04-24 }}</ref> and North Plains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid%3D27 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205035943/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=27 |archivedate=2012-02-05 }}</ref>\n\nThere are three middle schools in the system: the two in Minot are grades 6-8: Jim Hill in the south,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid%3D8 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205040124/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=8 |archivedate=2012-02-05 }}</ref> and Erik Ramstad in the north.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid%3D11 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716215801/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=11 |archivedate=2012-07-16 }}</ref> Memorial Middle School on Minot AFB,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid%3D2 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205040130/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=2 |archivedate=2012-02-05 }}</ref> is named for fallen veterans of the U.S. [[armed forces]]. The school was built in the mid-1960s on the northern perimeter of the base. All three middle schools were formerly called \"junior high\" schools.\n\nThe city has one public high school, [[Minot High School]], divided between two campuses. A few blocks east of [[Downtown Minot]] is Central Campus (grades 9-10),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/mps/cc/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208121407/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/mps/cc/ |archivedate=2016-02-08 }}</ref> which occupies the original high school building. On the southwest side of the city is the newer Magic City Campus (grades 11-12),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=33 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205040322/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=33 |archivedate=2012-02-05 }}</ref> constructed in 1973 just west of Jim Hill Middle School. MPS also operates an [[adult learning]] center and Souris River Campus, an [[alternative high school]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=34 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716215825/http://www.minot.k12.nd.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=34 |archivedate=2012-07-16 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pages.minot.k12.nd.us/mps/cc/history/school.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-02-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080131234242/http://pages.minot.k12.nd.us/mps/cc/history/school.html |archivedate=2008-01-31 }}</ref>\n\nPrivate schools in Minot include Bishop Ryan Catholic School, which offers preschool through grade 12 at a single campus. There is also a [[Protestant]] K-12 school, [[Our Redeemer's Christian School]].\n\nMinot is also home to [[Minot State University]], the third largest university in the state. MSU's campus is at the base of North Hill, just west of Broadway. Originally a two-year teacher's college when opened in 1913, Minot State became a university in 1987.\n\n===Preschool and daycare===\nMost of the larger daycare centers and pre-schools in the Minot area work in collaboration with local church groups. There are also programs such as [[Head Start (program)|Head Start]] and [[preschool]] programs through Minot Public Schools. The in-home daycare providers are state registered and licensed.\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Minot-StaveChurch.jpg|300px|thumb|right|The \"[[Gol Stave Church]]\" in Minot's Scandinavian Heritage Park]]\n[[File:Minot-DalaHorse.jpg|200px|thumb|right| The \"[[Dalecarlian horse|Dala horse]]\" in the Scandinavian Heritage Park]]\nMinot's arts community includes an art museum, a [[symphony orchestra]], an opera company, a city band, several dance and theater troupes, a youth/punk concert organization, and [[the AMP]]; over 40 organizations claim membership in the Minot Area Council on the Arts.\n\nNearly 40% of the city's residents are of [[Scandinavia]]n ancestry, and every October since 1977, Minot has been the host to the [[Norsk H\u00f8stfest]], North America's largest Scandinavian-American festival. [[Scandinavian Heritage Park]] is located in Minot. Scandinavian Heritage Park features remembrances and replicas from each of the Scandinavian countries: Sweden, Norway, Denmark, Finland, and Iceland.\n\n===Recreation===\nThe [[Minot Park District]] operates seventeen parks with various facilities; Corbett Field, home to American Legion, high school and college baseball; Optimist soccer complex; MAYSA ice arena; the Sertoma Complex which has 8 softball fields; Souris Valley Golf Course, and an indoor tennis complex.\n\nThe city's largest parks are [[Roosevelt Park (Minot)|Roosevelt Park]] and [[Oak Park, Minot, North Dakota|Oak Park]]. [[Roosevelt Park Zoo]] is one of the top zoos in the region. Dogs are allowed in Roosevelt Park, a sign is posted at the entrance confirming this. A \"bark park\" for dogs opened in the summer of 2005.\n\nThe [[North Dakota State Fair]] is held in July annually, in Minot. Nearly all recreation areas however are closed during the long winters. The local high school hockey teams use the ice rink located in the Fair Grounds. The ice rink is also turned into the location of the rodeo.\n\nApple Grove Golf Course, and [[Souris Valley Golf Course]] are located in Minot.\n\n===Sports===\n*The Minot Mallards, were a [[Mandak League]] baseball team that played their games at [[Corbett Field (Minot)|Corbett Field]].\n*The [[Minot Minotauros]], an [[North American Hockey League|NAHL]] team, play their games at [[Maysa Arena]].\n*The Minot Muskies, played one season with the [[American West Hockey League]] and played their games at [[All Seasons Arena (Minot)|All Seasons Arena]].\n*The Minot Americans were an SJHL hockey club from 1987 to 1994, playing their games primarily at All Seasons Arena.\n*The Minot Top Guns were an SJHL hockey club from 1994 to 1997, playing their games primarily at All Seasons Arena.\n*Other semi-professional hockey clubs calling Minot home were the Minot Raiders/Rangers ('75-'77) and the Minot Maple Leafs ('85-'86).\n*The [[Minot Skyrockets]], a former [[Continental Basketball Association]] team, played their games at [[Minot Municipal Auditorium]].\n*The [[Minot State Beavers]] play ice hockey at [[All Seasons Arena (Minot)|All Seasons Arena]], baseball at [[Corbett Field (Minot)|Corbett Field]], football at [[Herb Parker Stadium]] and basketball at the [[MSU Dome]].\n*The Mouse River Rollers play roller derby at different locations around the city, including the Maysa Arena.\n* Minot is home to several municipal sports venues including the [[All Seasons Arena (Minot)|All Seasons Arena]], [[Corbett Field (Minot)|Corbett Field]], [[Maysa Arena]] and the [[Minot Municipal Auditorium]].\n\n===Sister cities===\nMinot maintains a [[sister city]] relationship with the [[Norway|Norwegian]] city of [[Skien]].\n\nMinot is also a sister city of [[Moose Jaw, Saskatchewan|Moose Jaw]], [[Saskatchewan]], about {{convert|300|mi|km}} to the north-west. The cities share many qualities, including their size, location on river valleys, historical origins, and air force bases.\n\n==Media==\n{{Main|Media in Minot, North Dakota}}\nMinot has several media outlets. [[KMOT-TV]], [[KXMC-TV]] and the [[Minot Daily News]] report on local news daily. KCJB-AM, KHRT-AM, and [[Prairie Public (disambiguation)|Prairie Public]] have some local news content, but no active journalists.\n\n=== Radio ===\nMinot is served by fifteen radio stations (12 FM, 3 AM). [[Bottineau, North Dakota|Bottineau]]-based [[Programmer's Broadcasting]] owns [[KTZU]] and [[KWGO]], along with [[KBTO]] of [[Bottineau, North Dakota|Bottineau]]. [[Prairie Public Radio]] operates [[KMPR]] FM 88.9, a local community broadcaster based in [[Burlington, North Dakota|Burlington]] operates a [[LPFM|low-power]] FM station, and the remainder are nonprofit Christian stations, of which only KHRT is based locally.\n\n[[iHeartMedia]] owns and operates all of the commercial stations licensed to Minot itself: [[KCJB]] 910 (Classic Country & Talk), [[KRRZ]] 1390 (Classic Hits/Talk), [[KYYX]] 97.1 (Country), [[KIZZ]] 93.7 (Top 40), [[KMXA-FM]] 99.9 (AC), and [[KZPR]] 105.3 (Active Rock). This concentration of broadcasting in the hands of one owner has led to criticism.<ref>Jennifer B. Lee, \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2003/03/31/business/media-on-minot-nd-radio-a-single-corporate-voice.html?pagewanted=all On Minot, N.D., Radio, A Single Corporate Voice], ''[[The New York Times]]'', Mar. 31, 2003.</ref><ref>Peter DiCola, \"[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/peter-dicola/the-debate-over-minot-rad_b_38421.html The Debate Over Minot Radio]\", ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', Jan. 11, 2007, updated May 25, 2011.</ref>\n\n==== AM frequencies ====\n* 910 [[KCJB]]: \"91 Country\" [[Country music|Country]]/[[Talk radio|Talk]]\n* 1320 [[KHRT]]: \"K-Heart\" [[Gospel music]]\n* 1390 [[KRRZ]]: \"Cars\" [[Classic hits]]\n* 710 [[KXMR]]: \"ESPN\" [[Sports talk]]\n\n==== FM Frequencies ====\n* 88.9 [[KMPR]]: [[Prairie Public Radio]]\n* 91.1 K216EE: [[Real Presence Radio]] [[Christian radio|Christian]]\n* 91.9 K220GC: [[Air1]] [[Christian radio|Christian]]\n* 93.7 [[KIZZ]]: \"Z94\" [[Top 40]]\n* 94.9 [[KTZU]]: \"The Zoo\" [[Classic rock]]\n* 97.1 [[KYYX]]: \"97 Kicks\" [[Country music|Country]]\n* 98.1 [[KOWW-LP]]: \"The Cowlip\" [[community radio|eclectic community broadcaster]] ([[Burlington, North Dakota|Burlington]], North Dakota)\n* 99.9 [[KMXA-FM]]: \"Mix 99.9\" [[Adult Contemporary]]\n* 100.7 [[KNDL (FM)|KNDL]]: [[K-Love]] [[Christian radio|Christian]]\n* 102.9 [[KWGO]]: \"W-G-O\" [[Country music|Country]]\n* 104.1 [[KSAF-LP]]: [[3ABN Radio]] [[Christian radio|Christian]]\n* 105.3 [[KZPR]]: \"The Fox\" [[Active Rock]]\n* 106.9 [[KHRT]]: \"K-Heart\" [[Christian radio|Christian]]\n\n==== Other stations ====\nAdditionally, the following stations are not based in Minot, but generally have a clear signal into town:\n\n*550 AM [[KFYR (AM)|KFYR]]: \"K-Fire\" from [[Bismarck, North Dakota|Bismarck]] ([[Talk radio|News/Talk/Sports]])\n*710 AM [[KXMR]]: [[ESPN]], also from [[Bismarck, North Dakota|Bismarck]] ([[Sports radio|Sports]])\n*1410 AM [[KDKT]]: \"[[Fox Sports Radio]] 1410\" also from [[Bismarck, North Dakota|Bismarck]] ([[Sports radio|Sports]])\n*101.9 FM [[KBTO]]: \"Sunny 101.9\" from [[Bottineau, North Dakota|Bottineau]] ([[Country music|Country]])\n\n=== Television ===\nMinot has six television stations, most of which have [[ATSC]] (digital) transmitters:\n\n*[[Prairie Public Television|KSRE]] ([[ATSC Standards|ATSC]] [[Radio frequency|RF]] channel 40); [[Program and System Information Protocol|virtual channels]] 6.1 [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]], 6.2 [[PBS World]], 6.3 [[Minnesota Channel]], 6.4 Lifelong Learning\n*[[KMOT]] ([[ATSC Standards|ATSC]] [[Radio frequency|RF]] channel 10); [[Program and System Information Protocol|virtual channels]] 10.1 [[NBC]], 10.2 [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]], 10.3 [[Me-TV]]\n*[[KXMC-TV]] ([[ATSC Standards|ATSC]] [[Radio frequency|RF]] channel 13); [[Program and System Information Protocol|virtual channels]] 13.1 [[CBS]], 13.3 The CW\n*[[KBMY|KMCY]]  ([[ATSC Standards|ATSC]] [[Radio frequency|RF]] channel 14); [[Program and System Information Protocol|virtual channels]] 14.1 [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n*[[KNDB|KNDM]] ([[ATSC Standards|ATSC]] [[Radio frequency|RF]] channel 24); [[Program and System Information Protocol|virtual channels]] 24.1 [[Heroes & Icons]]\n\n==== Cable service ====\n[[Midcontinent Communications]] provides cable service to the city of Minot and Minot Air Force Base. [[Souris River Telecommunications]] provides cable service to other nearby communities.\n\n=== Print ===\nThe principal local newspaper is the ''[[Minot Daily News]]'', which publishes seven days a week. The Minot Air Force Base also has a weekly newspaper printed, [http://www.northernsentry.com The Northern Sentry]. It is a free publication published on Fridays by BHG, Inc. out of Garrison, ND available on the MAFB, as well as the surrounding communities and many locations within Minot. The Minot State University student newspaper ''Red & Green'' is published once a week (Thursdays) during the regular school year, but not during the summer months. Morgan Printing produces the ''Lunch Letter'' three days a week on a double-sided leaflet. There is one weekly classified-ad publication, the ''Trading Post'', printed by the ''Minot Daily News''. The ''[[Bismarck Tribune]]'' is available at several outlets in the city, as is ''[[The Forum of Fargo-Moorhead|The Forum]]'', to a lesser extent.\n\n==Transportation==\n{{unreferenced section|date = September 2016}}\n\n===Railroads===\nThe railroads that built Minot remain, though Great Northern is now part of the [[BNSF Railway]] and the Soo Line is run by the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]].\n\nPassenger rail transportation is provided daily on [[Amtrak]]'s ''[[Empire Builder]]'' line, connecting Chicago with Portland and Seattle, which stops at the [[Minot (Amtrak station)|Minot Amtrak station]]. Trains make a 20-minute refueling and crew change stop in Minot; Westbound trains arrive about 9:00 am [[Central Standard Time Zone|local time]]. Eastbound trains arrive about 9:00 pm.\n\n===Highways===\n[[File:Minotwide.jpg|300 px|thumb|right|US 83 running through north Minot]]\n\nThree major U.S. highways run through the city, connecting it to Canada, Montana, and two interstates: [[U.S. Route 2 in North Dakota|US 2]], [[U.S. Route 52 in North Dakota|US 52]], and [[U.S. Route 83 in North Dakota|US 83]].\n\nUS 2 runs east-west and is a four-lane divided highway from Minot east to [[Grand Forks, North Dakota|Grand Forks]] and beyond as well as west to [[Williston, North Dakota|Williston]] and into Montana. Minot is midpoint along the North Dakota segment of US 2.\n\nUS 83 runs north-south through central Minot as [[Broadway (Minot, North Dakota)|Broadway]]. It is a four-lane divided highway from Minot south to [[Bismarck, North Dakota|Bismarck]] and north to [[Minot AFB, North Dakota|Minot Air Force Base]]. Just north of the main gate at the base, the road reduces to two lanes and crosses the Canada\u2013US border at [[Westhope, North Dakota|Westhope, ND]], where it becomes [[Manitoba]] Highway 83.\n\nUS 52 is a two-lane highway that runs southeast-northwest. Southeast from Minot, it follows a slightly circuitous route to [[Jamestown, North Dakota|Jamestown]]. US 52 then merges with [[Interstate 94]] (I-94) after Jamestown, heading due east to [[Fargo, North Dakota|Fargo]]. Northwest from Minot, US 52 crosses the Canada\u2013US border at [[Portal, North Dakota|Portal, ND]]/North Portal, [[Saskatchewan|SK]], where it becomes [[Saskatchewan Highway 39]].\n\nThe [[Minot Bypass]] follows alternate alignments of these roads around the city in its northwest and northeast quadrants, with southwest and southeast bypasses in preliminary planning stages.\n\n===Airport===\n[[Minot International Airport]] is served by four airlines as well as charters and air taxi service around North Dakota. [[Delta Air Lines]] offers up to six daily round trips to [[Minneapolis International Airport]], offering hundreds of daily connections. [[United Airlines]] offers four daily round trips to its [[Denver International Airport]] hub. [[Allegiant Air]] provides up to four weekly round trips to Las Vegas [[McCarran International Airport]] and up to five weekly round trips to [[Phoenix-Mesa Gateway Airport]].\n\n===Within the city===\nAutomobiles dominate intracity and local area transport. There is limited fixed-route city transit service ([[Minot City Transit]]) on weekdays, and flexible-route rural transit service ([[Souris Basin Transportation]]) on an occasional basis. Local transit services for the elderly and disabled ([[Minot Commission on Aging Transit]]) meet federal guidelines but have 24-hour advance notice requirements.\n\nPedestrianism in the city is inhibited by several factors; the sidewalk network is poor in many areas of the city, though improving. Automobile drivers take the right of way at all but the best-marked crosswalks, and major points are often separated by relatively large distances and hill slopes. [[Skateboarding]] is illegal in streets and on sidewalks (though there is a skating area in Roosevelt Park), and [[rollerblading]] is generally disallowed by downtown landowners.\n\n==Sites of interest==\n[[File:2009-0521-ND-Minot-ScanHerPark-StaveChurch.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Scandinavian Heritage Park]]\n* [[Arlene Theater]], a performing arts center, where the Mouse River Players perform\n* [[Dakota Territory Air Museum]] is an [[aircraft]] museum near the airport. It contains many war and civilian aircraft.\n* [[Scandinavian Heritage Park]] is home to the Minot Visitor's Center, as well as buildings based on the Scandinavian style of architecture, including a Stave Church. The grounds are home to the Minot's Arts in the Park series.\n* [[Old Soo Depot Transportation Museum]], museum and research center in the restored 1912 Soo Line Depot.\n* [[North Dakota State Fair]] Center, located on the state fairgrounds, is home to many of the city's largest events, including: The [[North Dakota State Fair]], the [[Norsk H\u00f8stfest]], the Big One craft show, the KMOT Ag Expo, and the Great Tomato Festival. It also hosts rodeos, and college hockey games.\n* [[Roosevelt Park (Minot)|Roosevelt Park]] and [[Roosevelt Park Zoo|Zoo]]\n* [[Taube Museum of Art]], located in the 1906 Union National Bank Building, features exhibit space in the Main Gallery and the Lower Gallery, which change every four to six weeks.\n\n==Notable people==\n<!-- Note:\n\u00b7 Only people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here. This establishes notability.\n\u00b7 The article must mention how they are associated with <city name>, whether born, raised, or residing.\n\u00b7 The fact of their association should have a reliable source cited, unless it is well-known.\n\u00b7 Alphabetical by last name please.\n\u00b7 All others will be deleted without further explanation.\n-->\nThe following is a list of notable people who were either born in, are current residents of, or have lived in Minot.\n\n{{div col}}\n* [[Nicole Borud]], contestant on ''[[America's Next Top Model]]''\n* [[Ashton Smith]], movie trailer king\n* [[Ronnie Bradford]], [[NFL]] defensive back, [[2017 USC Trojans football team|USC]] assistant coach\n* [[Dale Brown (basketball)|Dale Brown]], [[Louisiana State Tigers men's basketball|LSU]] basketball coach\n* [[Gary Cederstrom]], [[MLB]] umpire\n* [[Jonny Craig]], musician and vocalist\n* [[Josh Duhamel]], actor\n* [[Ron Erhardt]], football coach\n* [[Marneen Fields]], actress, stuntwoman, and musician\n* [[Hans Andersen Foss]], Norwegian-born author, newspaper editor and temperance leader\n* [[Brynhild Haugland]], North Dakota House of Representatives member\n* [[Randy Hedberg]], NFL quarterback\n* [[John Hoeven]], 31st [[List of Governors of North Dakota|Governor of North Dakota]], later [[U.S. Senate|Senator]]\n* [[Christopher Michael Holley]], actor\n* [[Tim Jackman]], [[NHL]] athlete\n* [[Gary Johnson]], 29th [[Governor of New Mexico]]; the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]]'s [[2012 United States presidential election|2012]] & [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]] presidential candidate\n* [[Simon Johnson (novelist)|Simon Johnson]], Norwegian-born author and newspaper editor\n* [[David Charles Jones|David C. Jones]], U.S. Air Force General, [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]] from 1978\u201382\n* [[Boris Karloff]], actor\n* [[James Kerzman]], North Dakota House of Representatives member\n* [[Wiz Khalifa]], rapper, musician\n* [[Dagny Knutson]], swimmer\n* [[Mark Landsberger]], [[NBA]] athlete\n* [[Arthur LeSueur]], 9th [[Mayors of Minot, North Dakota|Mayor of Minot]], newspaper editor and organizer of the [[Socialist Party of North Dakota]]\n* [[Kevin Miller (voice actor)|Kevin Miller]], video game voice actor.\n* [[Michael H. Miller]], U.S. Navy rear admiral\n* [[Kathryn Morgan]], ballet dancer, vlogger\n* [[Herro Mustafa]], [[Iraqi Kurdistan]]-born American diplomat and advisor\n* [[Ragnvald A. Nestos]], 13th [[List of Governors of North Dakota|Governor of North Dakota]]\n* [[Casper Oimoen]], ski jumper\n* [[Mary Osborne]], jazz guitarist\n* [[Ken Paxton]], 51st [[Attorney General of Texas]]\n* [[Erik Ramstad]], founder of Minot\n* [[Greg Raymer]], 2004 [[World Series of Poker]] winner\n* [[Clinton Romesha]], [[Medal of Honor]] recipient\n* [[Donny Schatz]], race car driver\n* [[Eric Sevareid]], television journalist\n* [[Don Simensen]], football player\n* [[Michael Soltis]], actor and abstract artist\n* [[Charles F. Wald]], Deputy Commander of [[United States European Command]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Minot Why Nots]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Minot, North Dakota}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Minot}}\n*[http://www.minotnd.org City of Minot]\n*[http://www.visitminot.org/ Convention and Visitors Bureau]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100603152627/https://www.minotstateu.edu/library/ecoll_nd_03.shtml Minot history (MSU)]\n\n{{Ward County, North Dakota}}\n{{North Dakota}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Minot, North Dakota| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in North Dakota]]\n[[Category:Cities in Ward County, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:County seats in North Dakota]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1886]]\n", "name_user": "NotAThomas", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCulture:I slightly altered it so it was more accurate.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minot,_North_Dakota"}
{"title_page": "Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance Company Limited\n| logo                = \n| type                = [[Limited company|Limited]]\n| industry            = Insurance Services\n| foundation          = 2001\n| location_city       = [[Pune]]\n| location_country    = India\n| area_served         = Worldwide\n| key_people          = Tarun Chugh (MD & CEO) <ref>{{cite web|title=Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/bajaj-allianz-life-insurance-appoints-tarun-chugh-as-md-and-ceo-117040100617_1.html|accessdate=1 Apr 2017|publisher=business-standard.com}}</ref>\n| products            = [[Life Insurance]]\n| parent              = [[Bajaj Finserv]], [[Allianz SE]]\n| assets              = [[Indian rupee|INR]] 56,620 Cr <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bajajallianzlife.com/pdf/annual-report/BALIC-Annual-Report-15-16.pdf|format=PDF|title=Annual Report 2015-2016|publisher=bajajallianzlife}}</ref>\n| homepage            = {{URL|https://www.bajajallianzlife.com}}\n}}\n'''Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance''' is a joint venture between [[Bajaj Finserv]] Limited (formerly part of [[Bajaj Auto]] Limited) owned by the Bajaj Group of India and [[Allianz SE]], a European financial services company. Being one of the private insurance companies in India, it offers [[insurance]] products for financial planning and security.<ref name=businessweek>{{cite web|title=\nCompany Overview of Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance Company Limited|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=9155888|publisher=investing.businessweek.com|accessdate=10 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIt is led by Tarun Chugh who is the Managing director and Chief Executive Officer of the company. <ref name=bloomberg>{{cite web|title=Company new CEO and MD - Tarun Chugh|url=https://www.peoplematters.in/news/c-suite/tarun-chugh-appointed-as-md-and-ceo-for-bajaj-allianz-life-insurance-15255|publisher=peoplematters.in}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nBajaj Allianz Life Insurance began operations on 12 March 2001 and today has a [[Pan-Indianism|pan-India]] presence of 759 branches.<ref name=newsvoir>{{cite web|title=Bajaj Allianz Life Gets CARE AAA Rating for the Second Consecutive Year|url=http://www.newsvoir.com/release/bajaj-allianz-life-gets-care-aaa-rating-for-the-second-consecutive-year-3555.html|publisher=newsvoir.com|accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref> It is headquartered in [[Pune]], India. Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance received the [[Insurance Regulatory and Development Authority]] (IRDA) certificate of Registration on 3 August 2001 to conduct [[Life Insurance]] [[business]] in India.<ref name=smartinvestments>{{cite web|title=Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance company Info|url=http://www.smartinvestments.co.in/content/Information/companyprofile.asp?InsuCode=7&InsuCateCode=1|publisher=smartinvestments.com}}</ref>\n\n==Products and Services==\n\nBajaj Allianz [[Life Insurance]] offers a range of insurance services, operating through Participating, Non-Participating, and Linked segments.\n\nBajaj Allianz Life Insurance launches digital branches through Mosambee. Mosambee is a handheld device that offers the services of a mobile branch and assists customers with an entire range of customer services.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://www.bajajallianzlife.com}}\n\n{{Insurance in India}}\n\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Life insurance companies of India]]\n[[Category:Bajaj Group]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Pune]]\n[[Category:Multinational joint-venture companies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name             = Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance Company Limited\n|logo             = \n\n|type             = [[Limited company|Limited]]\n|industry         = Insurance Services  \n|foundation       = 2001\n|location_city    = [[Pune]]\n|location_country = India\n|area_served      = Worldwide\n|key_people       = Tarun Chugh (MD & CEO) <ref>{{cite web|title=Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/bajaj-allianz-life-insurance-appoints-tarun-chugh-as-md-and-ceo-117040100617_1.html|accessdate=1 Apr 2017|publisher=business-standard.com}}</ref>\n|products         = [[Life Insurance]]\n|parent           = [[Bajaj Finserv]], [[Allianz SE]]\n|assets           = [[Indian rupee|INR]] 4,361,583<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bajajallianzlife.com/pdf/annual-report/BALIC-Annual-Report-15-16.pdf|format=PDF|title=Annual Report 2015-2016|publisher=bajajallianzlife}}</ref>\n|homepage         = {{URL|https://www.bajajallianzlife.com}}\n}}\n'''Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance''' is a joint venture between [[Bajaj Finserv]] Limited (formerly part of [[Bajaj Auto]] Limited) owned by the Bajaj Group of India and [[Allianz SE]], a European financial services company. Being one of the private insurance companies in India, it offers [[insurance]] products for financial planning and security.<ref name=businessweek>{{cite web|title=\nCompany Overview of Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance Company Limited|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=9155888|publisher=investing.businessweek.com|accessdate=10 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIt is led by Tarun Chugh who is the Managing director and Chief Executive Officer of the company. <ref name=bloomberg>{{cite web|title=Company new CEO and MD - Tarun Chugh|url=https://www.peoplematters.in/news/c-suite/tarun-chugh-appointed-as-md-and-ceo-for-bajaj-allianz-life-insurance-15255|publisher=peoplematters.in}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nBajaj Allianz Life Insurance began operations on 12 March 2001 and today has a [[Pan-Indianism|pan-India]] presence of 759 branches.<ref name=newsvoir>{{cite web|title=Bajaj Allianz Life Gets CARE AAA Rating for the Second Consecutive Year|url=http://www.newsvoir.com/release/bajaj-allianz-life-gets-care-aaa-rating-for-the-second-consecutive-year-3555.html|publisher=newsvoir.com|accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref> It is headquartered in [[Pune]], India. Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance received the [[Insurance Regulatory and Development Authority]] (IRDA) certificate of Registration on 3 August 2001 to conduct [[Life Insurance]] [[business]] in India.<ref name=smartinvestments>{{cite web|title=Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance company Info|url=http://www.smartinvestments.co.in/content/Information/companyprofile.asp?InsuCode=7&InsuCateCode=1|publisher=smartinvestments.com}}</ref>\n\n==Products and Services==\n\nBajaj Allianz [[Life Insurance]] offers a range of insurance services, operating through Participating, Non-Participating, and Linked segments.\n\nBajaj Allianz Life Insurance launches digital branches through Mosambee. Mosambee is a handheld device that offers the services of a mobile branch and assists customers with an entire range of customer services.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://www.bajajallianzlife.com}}\n\n{{Insurance in India}}\n\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Life insurance companies of India]]\n[[Category:Bajaj Group]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Pune]]\n[[Category:Multinational joint-venture companies]]\n", "name_user": "ShaFai15", "label": "safe", "comment": "Total Asset Under Control is INR 56,620 Cr", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bajaj_Allianz_Life_Insurance"}
