{"title_page": "Richard Gough", "text_new": "{{about|the Scottish football player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Richard Gough\n| image       =\n| fullname    = Charles Richard Gough<ref>{{Hugman|7515|accessdate=14 May 2017}}</ref>\n| height      = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1962|4|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n| currentclub =\n| position    = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 = 1978\u20131979\n| youthclubs1 = [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]\n| youthyears2 = 1979\u20131980\n| youthclubs2 = [[Bidvest Wits|Wits University]]\n| years1 = 1980\u20131986 | caps1 = 165 | goals1 = 23 | clubs1 = [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n| years2 = 1986\u20131987 | caps2 = 49  | goals2 = 2  | clubs2 = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n| years3 = 1987\u20131997 | caps3 = 294 | goals3 = 25 | clubs3 = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| years4 = 1997      | caps4 = 17  | goals4 = 0  | clubs4 = [[Kansas City Wizards]]\n| years5 = 1997\u20131998 | caps5 = 24  | goals5 = 1  | clubs5 = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| years6 = 1998\u20131999 | caps6 = 19  | goals6 = 2  | clubs6 = [[San Jose Clash]]\n| years7 = 1999      | caps7 = 7   | goals7 = 0  | clubs7 = \u2192 [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] (loan)\n| years8 = 1999\u20132001 | caps8 = 38  | goals8 = 1  | clubs8 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]\n| totalcaps      = 613\n| totalgoals     = 54\n| nationalyears1 = 1983\u20131993\n| nationalteam1  = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 61\n| nationalgoals1 = 6\n| manageryears1  = 2004\u20132005\n| managerclubs1  = [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]]\n}}\n'''Charles Richard Gough''' (born 5 April 1962) is a Scottish former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]].\n\nGough was first noticed in the successful [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] team of the early 1980s, winning the [[list of Scottish football champions|Scottish league title]] in [[1982\u201383 in Scottish football|1982\u201383]] and reaching the [[European Cup]] semi-final in [[1983\u201384 European Cup|1984]]. Gough captained [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in the [[1987 FA Cup Final]]. He then captained [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] to nine successive Scottish league titles. He also played for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] 61 times and played in the finals of three major international tournaments.\n\nGough had a brief spell as [[manager (association football)|manager]] of [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]] and is currently global ambassador for [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn to a Scottish father (former [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] player [[Charlie Gough]]) and a Swedish mother, Gough grew up in South Africa. He went to school at [[King Edward VII School (Johannesburg)|King Edward VII and Highlands North High School]] in Johannesburg, and began his career playing with the [[Wits University F.C.|Wits University]] club.\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Club===\nGough signed for Charlton Athletic as an apprentice professional in July 1978. However, he returned to play for Wits University for a brief period in 1979.\n\nGough signed for [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] in February 1980. He played for Dundee United for six seasons finishing with 23 goals in 165 appearances. Gough helped them to the Scottish League title in 1982\u201383. Dundee United also reached the [[1983\u201384 European Cup]] semi-final against [[AS Roma|Roma]] during his time at the club.\n\nIn 1986, Gough was sold to English First Division club [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] for [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]750,000 He played for slightly over a year and captained the Tottenham team which lost to [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] in the [[1987 FA Cup Final]].\n\nGough decided to return to Scotland, joining Rangers early in the 1987\u201388 season. In making the move he became the first Scottish player to be transferred for over \u00a31,000,000. His debut was at [[Tannadice Park]], in a defeat against former club Dundee United. He was named the [[SFWA Footballer of the Year]] in 1988/89. Gough remained at [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]] until 1997, captaining the side that achieved nine consecutive League titles. He won 9 league titles, 3 Scottish Cups and 6 League Cups at Rangers. In all, he played 427 league games with Rangers, scoring 37 goals.\n\nIn May 1997, Gough left the United Kingdom to play in the United States' nascent professional league, [[Major League Soccer]], signing for [[Kansas City Wizards]]. In October 1997, he returned to Rangers due to injury issues at Ibrox. He resumed his MLS career with the [[San Jose Clash]]. He played 36 games in total in MLS, scored 2 goals and he was named the [[MLS Best XI]] for his 1997 season with the Wizards. Gough also went on loan [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] from March until May 1999, playing seven matches as the club was relegated.\n\nAfter leaving San Jose Clash he linked up with former boss [[Walter Smith]] at [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]. He played two seasons at [[Goodison Park]] making 60 appearances and scoring once against Southampton.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-jeffers-and-campbell-offer-hope-1114467.html |title=Jeffers and Campbell offer hope |work=[[The Independent]] |date=21 August 1999 |accessdate=7 November 2009 | location=London | first=Richard | last=Slater}}</ref> During his time at Everton he was made captain for 2000/01 season and retired from playing in May 2001.<ref>{{ cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/everton/1307334.stm | title=Gough calls it a day | date=1 May 2001 | publisher=BBC | work=BBC | accessdate=15 October 2014 }}</ref>\n\nGough agreed to play as a guest for Australian team [[Gladesville Hornsby Football Association Spirit FC|Northern Spirit]] in October 2001, but had to withdraw due to injury.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2001/10/04/spirit-loses-gough |title=Spirit loses Gough |work= |publisher=SBS |date=4 October 2001 |accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===International===\nGough was also a regular in the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]] in the 1980s. He made his debut against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] in 1983, and went on to gain 61 caps. Gough played in two World Cups ([[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]] and [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990]]). He captained his country in the [[UEFA Euro 1992|1992 European Championships]] in his birthplace, Sweden.\n\nGough scored six international goals. In 1985, he scored the only goal of the game when Scotland beat [[England national football team|England]] 1\u20130 at [[Hampden Park]]. He scored two goals in February 1989 in a 3\u20132 World Cup qualifier win away to [[Cyprus national football team|Cyprus]], with the second being scored in the sixth minute of added time.\n\nHis international career was ended prematurely, however, after he was critical of coaches [[Andy Roxburgh]] and [[Craig Brown (footballer, born 1940)|Craig Brown]] and withdrew himself from further selection.\n\n==Managerial career==\nOn 30 November 2004, Gough landed his first and only managerial position with the then [[Scottish Premier League]] side [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]].<ref>{{ cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/livingston/4043875.stm | title=Gough named Livingston boss | work=BBC Sport | date=30 November 2004 }}</ref> After a difficult season where the club battled relegation, Gough resigned and cited disagreements with the club's owner over the budget for signing players as the reason.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/article438407.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=You want to sack me Just do it | first=Simon | last=Buckland | date=27 March 2005 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{ cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/livingston/4557115.stm | title=Manager Gough to leave Livingston | work=BBC Sport | date=17 May 2005 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> The club was also fined \u00a315,000 by the SFA for a breach of transfer regulations over the signing of [[Hassan Kachloul]] during Gough's time as manager<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/l/livingston/4602415.stm |work=BBC Sport| title=Livi fined over Kachloul signing | date=15 June 2005 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> although there was no suggestion that Gough himself was responsible for the breach of regulations.\n\n==Later career==\nGough supported the [[Rangers Supporters' Trust]] and [[Dave King (businessman)|Dave King]]'s boardroom takeover of [[Ownership of Rangers F.C.|Rangers International Football Club PLC]] and was later appointed as a global ambassador for the club on 21 September 2015.<ref name=\"Gough named global ambassador\">{{ cite news | url=http://rangers.co.uk/news/headlines/gough-named-global-ambassador/ | title=Gough named global ambassador | date=21 September 2015 | publisher=Rangers.co.uk | work=Rangers Football Club }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGough has resided in San Diego, California, since 1997.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2018/august/catching-up-with-richard-gough/ |title=Catching up with Richard Gough |work= |publisher=Tottenham Hotspur |date=6 August 2018 |accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===International appearances===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.national-football-teams.com/player/16379/Richard_Gough.html|title=Richard Gough|first=Benjamin|last=Strack-Zimmermann|website=www.national-football-teams.com}}</ref>\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1983||11||1\n|